== Current Situation ==
Yes, {{project_name_long}} can be used on a USB. [[File:logo-usb-500x500.png|45px]]

# Install Debian on USB.
# Distribution morph Debian into {{project_name_long}}.

At this time, {{project_name_long}} does not provide a USB creator / image.

There are a number of online guides explaining how to install Debian on a USB.

If it is actually booting into non-persistent live boot is what you're interested in, look into live mode.
{{live}}

Specifically useful is {{project name long}} in combination with the default pre-installed <code>grub-live</code> software package which makes it possible to boot the host operating system into [[Host Live Mode]].

== Advantages ==
A higher level of security is attained by installing the host operating system(s) required for {{project_name_long}} on a dedicated, ([[Full Disk Encryption|encrypted]]), external disk(s) like a USB flash drive or others. <ref>
* FireWire - best avoided
** https://louwrentius.com/firewire-the-forgotten-security-risk.html
** https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_1394#Security_issues
* eSATA
</ref> 

* Using external media reduces the risk of other operating system(s) infecting the {{project_name_long}} host operating system. 
* When {{project_name_long}} disk(s) are not in use, they can either be removed or hidden.

